{"key":"post-11908068","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>11908068</id>\n<content>It's true that not having holes in the side will increase the amount of air entering the bottom holes and passing up and out the top.&amp;nbsp; However, you don't just want fresh air; green molds suffer and mushrooms thrive in turbulent air, thus the holes in the sides increase total fresh air movement and exchange.&amp;nbsp; I experimented for nearly a year with that exact design before finally going with the shotgun with holes on all six sides.&amp;nbsp; Both perform, but in my experience, consistent performance was better with the holes on all six sides.&amp;nbsp; It will be interesting to see your results after several runs, which would tend to equalize out the variations caused by multispore inoculation.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;One viable explanation for the size discrepancy could be the increased amount of FAE and the lack of enough misting to replace the extra lost moisture in the substrates.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>11908394</next>\n<prev>11908004</prev>\n<first>11900750</first>\n<last>11908394</last>\n<when>1264563850</when>\n<utime>01/27/10 05:44 AM</utime>\n</post>"}